(Work Group:    Library Clause 17)312 1281 MS
(Issue Number:  17-001)312 1321 MS
(Title:         Header Inclusion Policy)312 1361 MS
(Section:       17.3.4.1  [)312 1401 MS
(lib.res.on.headers])910 1401 MS
(Status:        Open)312 1441 MS
(Description:)312 1481 MS
(The \(original\) header inclusion policy of allowing any C++ header to include)312 1561 MS
(any other C++ header creates portability problems for users.  For example, the)312 1601 MS
(following might compile correctly with some implementations and fail with)312 1641 MS
(others:)312 1681 MS
(#include <string>  // programmer meant to write <)462 1761 MS
(iostream>)1589 1761 MS
(using namespace std;)462 1801 MS
(int main\(\) {)462 1841 MS
(   )462 1881 MS
(cout << "Hello, C++ World" << )531 1881 MS
(endl;)1221 1881 MS
(   return 0;)462 1921 MS
(   })462 1961 MS
(The \(current\) header inclusion policy of specifying exactly which C++ headers)312 2041 MS
(include which other C++ headers causes difficulty for implementors.  The worst)312 2081 MS
(case is when one header requires reference to another but the other is not)312 2121 MS
(specified as included.  Another troublesome case occurs when the)312 2161 MS
(implementation of one header \(like <complex>\) could benefit from access to)312 2201 MS
(something in another header \(like template )312 2241 MS
(numeric_limits in <limits>\).)1301 2241 MS
(The LWG has discussed these problems at length, and explored several)312 2321 MS
(alternatives including )312 2361 MS
(implementor's namespaces \(rejected because they don't)841 2361 MS
(allow template )312 2401 MS
(specializations by users\).  The approach discussed in Santa)657 2401 MS
(Cruz is to:)312 2441 MS
(-- Put more effort into correcting the synopsis lists of required)462 2521 MS
(header #includes.  Sensible inclusion minimizes both )462 2561 MS
(implementor's and)1681 2561 MS
(user's problems.)462 2601 MS
(-- Continue to require inclusion of headers listed in synopsis, but)462 2681 MS
(also allow inclusion of names from other headers.  This allows a user)462 2721 MS
(to write portable programs \(by only relying on names from the required)462 2761 MS
(headers\), allows automatic diagnosis of non-portable programs, and yet)462 2801 MS
(also gives )462 2841 MS
(implementor's access to names they want and need.)715 2841 MS
(Resolution:)312 2921 MS
